  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(2/3\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(3\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(1/3\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
</question>
<!-- Q9 --><question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>Series - Dirichlet Test</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>The series \(\displaystyle\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{\sin n}{n}\) converges by which test?</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (B) Dirichlet's test</strong></p><p>Dirichlet's test: if \(\{b_n\}\) is monotone decreasing to 0 and the partial sums of \(\{a_n\}\) are bounded, then \(\sum a_n b_n\) converges. Here \(a_n=\sin n\) has bounded partial sums (since \(\sum_{k=1}^N\sin k=\text{Im}\sum_{k=1}^N e^{ik}\) is bounded), and \(b_n=1/n\searrow0\). So \(\sum\sin(n)/n\) converges.</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[Ratio test]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="100" format="html"><text><![CDATA[Dirichlet's test]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[Comparison test with \(\sum 1/n^2\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[Root test]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
</question>
<!-- Q10 --><question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>Series - Basel Problem</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>The exact sum \(\displaystyle\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{n^2}\) equals:</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (C) \(\pi^2/6\)</strong></p><p>This is the Basel problem, solved by Euler (1734). \(\sum_{n=1}^\infty\frac{1}{n^2}=\frac{\pi^2}{6}\approx1.6449\ldots\). Euler's proof used the factorization of \(\sin x/x=\prod_{n=1}^\infty(1-x^2/n^2\pi^2)\) and comparing coefficients.</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(\pi/4\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(\ln 2\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="100" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(\pi^2/6\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(e-1\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
</question>
<!-- Q11 --><question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>Series - Raabe's Test</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>Raabe's test is used when the ratio test gives \(L=1\). For \(\sum a_n\) with \(a_n>0\), Raabe's test uses \(\lim_{n\to\infty}n\left(\dfrac{a_n}{a_{n+1}}-1\right)=R\). The series converges if:</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (A) \(R>1\)</strong></p><p>Raabe's test: if \(R=\lim n(a_n/a_{n+1}-1)>1\), the series converges; if \(R<1\), it diverges; if \(R=1\), inconclusive. This test handles borderline cases like \(\sum 1/(n\log n)\) where the ratio test fails.</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
  <answer fraction="100" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(R>1\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(R<1\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(R=1\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(R=0\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
</question>
<!-- Q12 --><question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>Series - Double Sum</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>The double series \(\displaystyle\sum_{m=1}^{\infty}\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{m^2 n^2}\) equals:</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (B) \(\pi^4/36\)</strong></p><p>Since both series converge absolutely, we can factor: \(\sum_{m,n}\frac{1}{m^2n^2}=\left(\sum_m\frac{1}{m^2}\right)\left(\sum_n\frac{1}{n^2}\right)=\frac{\pi^2}{6}\cdot\frac{\pi^2}{6}=\frac{\pi^4}{36}\).</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
