<!-- Q13 --><question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>Series - Riemann Rearrangement</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>By Riemann's rearrangement theorem, a <em>conditionally convergent</em> series can be rearranged to:</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (D) Converge to any prescribed real number, or diverge to \(\pm\infty\)</strong></p><p>Riemann's rearrangement theorem: if \(\sum a_n\) converges conditionally (but not absolutely), then for any \(L\in\mathbb{R}\cup\{\pm\infty\}\), there is a rearrangement converging to \(L\). This dramatically shows how conditionally convergent series are sensitive to order, unlike absolutely convergent ones.</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[Only converge to the same sum]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[Only diverge to \(\pm\infty\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[Only converge to a value in a small interval around the original sum]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="100" format="html"><text><![CDATA[Converge to any prescribed real number, or diverge to \(\pm\infty\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
</question>
<!-- Q14 --><question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>Series - Telescoping</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>The sum \(\displaystyle\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{n(n+2)}\) equals:</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (A) \(3/4\)</strong></p><p>Partial fractions: \(\frac{1}{n(n+2)}=\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{1}{n}-\frac{1}{n+2}\right)\). Sum = \(\frac{1}{2}\left[\left(1+\frac{1}{2}\right)-\lim_{N\to\infty}\left(\frac{1}{N+1}+\frac{1}{N+2}\right)\right]=\frac{1}{2}\cdot\frac{3}{2}=\frac{3}{4}\).</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
  <answer fraction="100" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(3/4\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(1/2\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(1\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
