<!-- Q15 --><question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>Series - Convergence of sum n!/n^n</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>The series \(\displaystyle\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{n!}{n^n}\) is:</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (B) Convergent</strong></p><p>By the ratio test: \(\frac{a_{n+1}}{a_n}=\left(\frac{n}{n+1}\right)^n\to e^{-1}<1\). So the series converges. By Stirling: \(n!/n^n\sim\sqrt{2\pi n}/e^n\to0\) exponentially fast, confirming rapid convergence.</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[Divergent]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="100" format="html"><text><![CDATA[Convergent]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[The ratio test is inconclusive]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[Convergent only conditionally]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
</question>
<!-- Q16 --><question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>Series - sum 1/(n log n)</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>The series \(\displaystyle\sum_{n=2}^{\infty}\frac{1}{n\ln n}\) is:</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (D) Divergent (by the integral test)</strong></p><p>Integral test: \(\int_2^\infty\frac{dx}{x\ln x}=[\ln(\ln x)]_2^\infty=\infty\). So the series diverges. In general \(\sum\frac{1}{n(\ln n)^p}\) converges iff \(p>1\).</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
