<!-- Q18 --><question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>Series - Convergence of sum 1/n^(1+1/n)</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>The series \(\displaystyle\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{n^{1+1/n}}\) is:</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (C) Divergent</strong></p><p>\(n^{1+1/n}=n\cdot n^{1/n}\to n\cdot1=n\). So \(\frac{1}{n^{1+1/n}}\sim\frac{1}{n}\), diverging like the harmonic series. More precisely, by limit comparison with \(1/n\): \(\frac{1/n^{1+1/n}}{1/n}=n^{-1/n}\to1>0\), so both diverge together.</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[Convergent (p-series with \(p>1\))]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[Convergent by the root test]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="100" format="html"><text><![CDATA[Divergent (limit comparison with \(\sum 1/n\))]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[The ratio test is conclusive and shows convergence]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
</question>
<!-- Q19 --><question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>Series - Abel's Test</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>Abel's test states: if \(\sum a_n\) converges and \(\{b_n\}\) is monotone and bounded, then:</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (B) \(\sum a_n b_n\) converges</strong></p><p>Abel's test: convergence of \(\sum a_n\) + monotone bounded \(\{b_n\}\) implies convergence of \(\sum a_n b_n\). This is a strengthening of Dirichlet's test (which requires \(b_n\to0\)). Abel summation (summation by parts) is the key tool in the proof.</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(\sum a_n b_n\) diverges]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="100" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(\sum a_n b_n\) converges]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(\sum a_n b_n\) converges absolutely]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(\sum a_n b_n^2\) converges]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
</question>
<!-- Q20 --><question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>Series - CSIR Style: Identify Convergent Series</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>Which of the following series is <strong>convergent</strong>?</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (D) \(\sum\frac{(-1)^n}{n^2}\)</strong></p><p>(A) \(\sum\frac{1}{\sqrt{n}}\): p-series with \(p=1/2<1\), diverges. (B) \(\sum\frac{n}{n+1}\): terms \(\to1\neq0\), diverges. (C) \(\sum\frac{1}{n\ln n}\): diverges (integral test). (D) \(\sum\frac{(-1)^n}{n^2}\): absolutely convergent since \(\sum\frac{1}{n^2}=\pi^2/6<\infty\).</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(\displaystyle\sum_{n=1}^\infty\frac{1}{\sqrt{n}}\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(\displaystyle\sum_{n=1}^\infty\frac{n}{n+1}\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
